all aboard
Homonym Number:
Word Class:phrase
Sense Number:2
Definition:Obs. [Transf. with pun on board the shearing floor.]A shearers' call, start work, start shearing! Contrast all on the board!
Origin:
Register:
Register 2:
Domain:[none]
Region:[none]
See:
Pronunciation:
Notes:
Citations
Date: 9/1/1907
Source: Tuapeka Times
Author:
Vol / Page: 4
Edition:
Quote: Yards full of sheep, dogs barking, men shouting, and the click, click of shears are the chaotic sounds and sights of a station in full shearing swing. Clear the board, all aboard, smoke-o, is the usual shearing vernacular heard in a shed.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1897
Source: Station Ballads
Author: McKEE WRIGHT
Vol / Page:
Edition:
Quote: `All aboard! All aboard!' is the cry./ They're a ripping lot of shearers in the shed;/ ... / `Wool away! Wool away!' is the cry/ And the merry game of busting is begun!/ They're going sheep and sheep, for Big Mick will do or die,/ And the fleecy boys are kept upon the run./ ... [fn] In old-time sheds these calls indicated the beginning and end of a run.
Notes: in 1950  Woodhouse Farm and Station Verse 33

